        Chart Review In Short 25/10/24

        Mr. I'm Too Good For A Surname is back chaps, and I'm guessing I got tons of backlash last week for not treating dead musicians with more respect than I should've. Not to be a pedantic or anything, but my commiserations to members of the afterlife depends on the music they made during their lifetimes. If someone like, say, Grian Chatten of Fontaines D.C. suddenly kicked the bucket, I would be bringing out the tearful emojis and sixth-form poetry to sum up how distraught I was. Meanwhile, if a dingus like Cian Durcot ended up popping his clogs, I'd have a hard time trying to keep my true feelings about the artist hidden while writing my condolences. Given Liam Payne is somewhat in the middle of these two categories, the words I put down stating how mid his solo career was probably ring true when compared to his somewhat more enjoyable One Direction days.

        And yes I'm stalling my thoughts on the charts, it's hardly the most eventful thing in the world nowadays is it? (Ignore all the mad things that's happened in 2024.)

        Anyways, this week's collection of hits and misses has 3 newbies in it, and just as many re-entries because of a certain Payne on my backside, Night Changes deciding to knock it's previous peak of No.7 out of the park, with Story Of My Life and What Makes You Beautiful also having a good time in the eyes of the fangirls. Speaking of which, ROS out of BLACKPINK might have officially ended up with the first K-POP song to not end up being frontloaded by the bots and the bees, although you can blame Bruno Mars for making APT. as good as it is. And by good, I mean slightly OK. In other news, Kylie Minogue achieves chart-topper number 10 on the album chart despite the singles from Tension II flopping to the end of the world, a deluxe edition of Gracie Abrams's album results in her grabbing another Top 20 success, and Morgan Wallen continues a one-man mission to prove that his endless riches on the Billboard charts can work wonders over here, with predictably mixed results. Sabrina's still No.1 by the way, but now her crown is under threat from surprise Spotify queen Gigi Perez, who now has the 2nd most popular song in the country and still hasn't impacted Capital's Big Top 40. To be fair, neither has Gracie Abrams, so every cloud and all that.

        Next week, there's new stuff from Lady Gaga, Disclosure, Mimi Webb, and a bunch of other artists who released C-tier material. Fight me.


        AMAZING TIER:

        Charli XCX [38], Chappell Roan [8], Linkin Park [33], Charli XCX [24], Shaboozey [28]

        GREAT TIER:

        Chappell Roan [15], Sabrina Carpenter [21] (End of an era. About dang time.), Adam Port/Stryv/Totally Hilarious Sight Gag Here [14]

I think I might throw up y'know.)

        ALL THE NEW STUFF*:

        ROS & Bruno Mars - APT. [4] (It may sound like two teenagers imitating HOT TO GO!, but it's lightyears ahead of any of her compatriots. Good for her I suppose.)

        *One Direction - Night Changes [6] (Gonna be honest with you, the 1D ballads are hardly my cup of tea. No matter how poignant they are, I still remain reluctant to them.)

        *One Direction - Story Of My Life [9] (I'd like it more if my mum wasn't obsessed with it.)

        Gracie Abrams - That's So True [19] (It sounds like most of her other singles, except with a tiny bit more pizzazz. Just like a true deluxe single should be.)

        *One Direction - What Makes You Beautiful [23] (Bit of an unorthodox choice to mourn to, isn't it?)

        Morgan Wallen - Love Somebody [40] (Better than his other hit, but not by much.)

        *Liam Payne ft. Quavo - Strip That Down [41] (Again, it's kinda difficult to grieve to a song that tells you to remove articles of clothing.)

        *Liam Payne/Rita Ora - For You [43] (Who else forgot this existed before he perished? Just me? Alright then.)

        Tyler, The Creator - NOID [50] (Only released on a Monday, so he has an excuse for this song doing poorly. Then again, with how it sounds like, I'm surprised he got as high as No.50.)

        JADE - Fantasy [52] (I don't care what Jools Holland thinks, her solo career is well on it's way to retirement already. That reunion can't come soon enough.)

        Wizkid ft. Brent Faiyaz - Piece Of My Heart [61] (The power of Afrobeats can only take you so far. Aside from that, it's a bit of a snoozefest this song.)

        George Michael - Careless Whisper [69] (A 40th anniversary re-release on 12" vinyl for completely no reason what-so-ever. No.12 in the midweeks by the way.)

        RAYE - Oscar Winning Tears. [75] (TikTok-powered energy for this album track. And it sounds as good as I've made it sound like. So not that much.)

        Liam Payne - Teardrops [85] (Originally flopped back in March, and for good reason. It just screams "generic ballad" through and through".)

        Brent Faiyaz - Best Time [89] (The album this is from turns 1 year old on Sunday if anyone's wondering. It's also a measly 82 seconds long. Blame TikTok again.)


        * = re-entry for an old song because of sympathy I presume


        See you in seven days when the trauma of Halloween catches up to everybody.
